│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The assertion in LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF() fails because the  │
│ VPlan-based cost model selects a scalar VF (BestFactor.Width == 1) while the  │
│ legacy cost model selects a vector VF (LegacyVF.Width == 2). The assertion    │
│ allows disagreement only if the chosen VPlan contains additional              │
│ simplifications not accounted for by the legacy cost model. The helper        │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications() incorrectly returns false in this     │
│ case, triggering the assertion.                                               │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The crash occurs immediately at the assertion, with BestFactor scalar and     │
│ LegacyVF vector. No debug output preceding shows any exceptional filtering of │
│ VFs. The loop is trivially vectorizable; the legacy model sees VF=2           │
│ profitable. The VPlan-based model chose scalar VF. The disagreement should    │
│ have been guarded by detecting simplifications, but                           │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications returned false.                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(), the loop over original IR         │
│ instructions calls CostCtx.skipCostComputation(&I, true) unconditionally      │
│ (line ~7329). Passing 'true' makes skipCostComputation consult both           │
│ ValuesToIgnore and VecValuesToIgnore. VecValuesToIgnore contains instructions │
│ that are dead only in vectorized versions. When BestFactor.Width is scalar,   │
│ those instructions are still live and should count toward detecting missing   │
│ recipes. Because the function always pretends it is analyzing a vector VF, it │
│ over-skips instructions and may fail to recognize that the VPlan omits them   │
│ without justification. Consequently, planContainsAdditionalSimplifications    │
│ returns false when it should return true, causing the assertion to fire       │
│ despite a legitimate cost-model disagreement due to simplifications only      │
│ present (or relevant) in vector form.                                         │
│ Thus the unconditional 'true' is wrong; the predicate must depend on whether  │
│ the VF under consideration is vector or scalar (BestFactor.Width.isVector()). │
│ The function currently has no way to know which VF is being validated;        │
│ computeBestVF passes no VF info. We must extend                               │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to take a flag (or VF) indicating       │
│ whether to treat vector-specific ignored instructions.                        │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Points(s):                                                   │
│ Edit Point 1 (lines 7286-7333): Modify the signature of                       │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to accept a bool IsVector (or           │
│ ElementCount VF) and use that instead of hard-coded 'true'. Change:           │
│ static bool planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(VPlan &Plan, VPCostContext  │
│ &CostCtx, Loop *TheLoop)                                                      │
│ To:                                                                           │
│ static bool planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(VPlan &Plan, VPCostContext  │
│ &CostCtx, Loop *TheLoop, bool IsVector)                                       │
│ And inside the return lambda replace skipCostComputation(&I, true) with       │
│ skipCostComputation(&I, IsVector).                                            │
│                                                                               │
│ Edit Point 2 (lines 7398-7401): Update the assertion call to pass             │
│ BestFactor.Width.isVector() to planContainsAdditionalSimplifications. Change: │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(getPlanFor(BestFactor.Width), CostCtx,  │
│ OrigLoop)                                                                     │
│ To:                                                                           │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(getPlanFor(BestFactor.Width), CostCtx,  │
│ OrigLoop, BestFactor.Width.isVector())                                        │
│                                                                               │
│ Rationale: This ensures vector-only ignored instructions are not suppressed   │
│ when validating a scalar VF. For scalar VF, IsVector=false causes             │
│ skipCostComputation to ignore VecValuesToIgnore, allowing the function to     │
│ detect that the VPlan omits instructions that the legacy model still costs,   │
│ thus returning true and satisfying the assertion condition.                   │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The fix aligns planContainsAdditionalSimplifications with the VF being        │
│ validated, preventing false negatives when validating scalar decisions. This  │
│ resolves the assertion by correctly identifying legitimate simplifications or │
│ ensuring disagreement logic does not trigger spuriously. No functional        │
│ behavior change beyond fixing debug assertion; release builds unaffected. The │
│ change is minimal, localized, and preserves existing logic for vector VFs.    │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
